Decision Tree of League of Legends Winner Prediction¶

Methods:¶

Riot Games created and released League of Legends (also known as LoL), a multiplayer online combat arena game, for Microsoft Windows and macOS. In League of Legends, players take on the role of an invisible "summoner" who commands a "champion" with special skills and engages in combat with a group of other players or champions that are being controlled by computers. Although there are other unique game types available, the objective is often to destroy the opponent team's "nexus," a building that sits at the center of a base secured by defensive structures. All champions in a League of Legends battle start off relatively weak, but as the game progresses, they gain experience and gear that make them stronger. Each League of Legends match is unique.

This section examined League of Legends rated matches and created a decision tree classification method to forecast match results. This algorithm was created by:

Winner (Team1 = 1, Team2 = 2)

Rift Herald, First Baron, Dragon, Tower, Blood, Inhibitor (1 = team1, 2 = team2), and Dragon, Tower, (1 = team2, 2 = team3)

Each team's total number of tower, inhibitor, baron, and dragon deaths

There were features.

Every piece of information came from the previous data gathering that have been cleaned.

Class Distribution:¶

Each side wants to safeguard its buildings and demolish the opposition's. Include:

Each lane is protected by towers. Teams have 11 towers.

Each lane has an inhibitor. After destroying the three lane turrets, a team may attack the Inhibitor.

Lower in the river are elder dragons and elemental drakes. Every squad member who kills the drake accumulates buffs throughout the game. Each drake's boost is based on the Four Elements. Six minutes after the last elemental drake is killed, a random one reappears. The Elder Dragon spawns after 35 minutes. It delivers a higher boost than a single elemental drake when killed, however it's transitory.

Rift Herald is a dangerous adversary on the upper riverbank. The Rift Herald may be revived and deployed to attack enemy towers.

Baron Nashor, a neutral antagonist, is on the river's upper bank. It replaces the Rift Herald after 20 minutes.

Each team has a Nexus, which can only be harmed if every turret, inhibitor, and Nexus turrets are downed. Destroying the opponent's Nexus ends the game.

first_team=data[data.winner==1]
second_team=data[data.winner==2]

The probability of several Features when a team wins are shown in the subplots that follow. For instance, when the first team wins a game, the likelihood of drawing first baron for the first team is around 49%. The likelihood of getting second team's first baron is roughly 13%. Any team's chance of drawing first blood is around 0.62. (early surrender When the second team wins, the likelihood of drawing first baron for the first team is around 12%. Taking the first baron for the opposing side has a 55% chance of happening. Any team's chances of getting first baron are roughly 67 percent (early surrender, etc.). Additionally, we can see that taking the first tower or inhibitor is crucial for winning games.

Feature Selection:¶

We looked for the optimal parameters to construct the best model. We utilized the grid search method to discover it.

In [ ]:
y = data["winner"].values
x = data.drop(["winner"], axis=1)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

Model Tuning:¶

In [ ]:
criterion = ["gini", "entropy"]
max_depth = range(1,20,2)
splitter = ["best", "random"]
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier()
grid_decision_tree = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt, cv=15, param_grid=dict(criterion=criterion,max_depth=max_depth,splitter=splitter))

Conclusion:¶

To sum up, There are countless factors to become variables that determine the victory of the game. However, in addtion, Players may offer an early surrender at the start of the LOL game if they are AFK. In this scenario, our model projects a 51%–49% victory generally if the first blood is not shed.

Anyway, the decision trees for this part are very quick and effective When campared to KNN and other classification algorithms. Simple to comprehend, interpret, and visualize. Whether the data is numerical, category, or boolean, decision trees can handle any form of data. The Decision Tree does not need normalization. But in the future, this may lead to the model being over-fit on the training set on high-dimensional datasets, overstating the accuracy of predictions on the training set, and preventing the model from properly predicting outcomes on the test set.

For general audience, decision tree can help them to evaluate their options when they play games and predict which team will win when they watch other players. It is an excellent tool for them to choose between several courses of action because it provides a very useful framework within which you may present alternatives and research the potential consequences of those options.
